\section{Regulatory conventions — column ordering}{

Standard pharma house styles and FDA/EMA submissions require:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Active treatment arm(s) left}, in order of dose escalation (lowest
to highest dose, left to right).
\item \strong{Comparator / placebo arm(s) rightmost} among the study arm columns.
\item \strong{Total column} (if included): optional; covers \strong{active arms only}
(does not pool active + placebo). Placed immediately after the
rightmost active arm column, before the placebo column.
}

Example column order for a 2-dose + placebo study:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode text">}}\preformatted{| Characteristic | Drug 10 mg | Drug 25 mg | Total (Active) | Placebo |
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\section{Label resolution order}{

Column labels are resolved in this priority (highest wins):
\enumerate{
\item N-count formatting (\code{fr_col(n=)} or \code{.n} + \code{.n_format}) — dynamic
label with N counts, applied at render time.
\item Explicit \code{fr_col(label = ...)} in \code{...} arguments.
\item \code{.list} — programmatic label map.
\item \code{.label_fn} — transform function applied to the column name.
\item Column name — the raw data frame column name as-is.
}
}

\section{Tips}{

\itemize{
\item Column order in the rendered table matches the \strong{data frame column
order}, not the order you list them in \code{fr_cols()}. To reorder
columns, reorder the data frame first.
\item Use \code{visible = FALSE} to suppress a column from rendering while keeping
it available as a grouping key for \code{\link[=fr_rows]{fr_rows()}}.
\item \code{align = "decimal"} aligns decimal points in numeric columns.
\item Width is in inches. Landscape Letter with 1 in margins gives 9 in
printable width. A common pharma layout: stub column 2.5 in + 4–5 data
columns at 1.3–1.5 in each.
\item \code{.width = "auto"} is the fastest way to get a working table — the
layout engine calculates widths from content. Use fixed widths only
when you need exact control.
\item \code{.label_fn} transforms \strong{only} auto-generated labels (column names
that were not explicitly relabelled). This lets you set a baseline
transform and override specific columns as needed.
}
}

